{"type":"message","id":"67ab2f3a","parentId":"c75f96fb","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:03:55.508Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Mon 2026-03-09 19:03 EST] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: # TASK: Test salesforce-code-auditor with Real Fixtures\n\n## CONTEXT\nThe `salesforce-code-auditor` skill is currently classified as PARTIAL because it hasn't been tested with real Salesforce metadata. The claim \"works if user supplies real code later\" is not sufficient proof of functionality.\n\n## PROBLEM ANALYSIS\nCurrent state (unproven):\n- Scripts exist and can be invoked\n- Not tested with real Salesforce metadata\n- Unknown if generates substantive findings\n- Unknown if outputs are consumable by architect\n- Functionality is theoretical, not proven\n\nRequired state (proven):\n- Tested with real Salesforce code samples\n- Generates substantive technical findings\n- Creates usable audit reports\n- Outputs are consumable by salesforce-architect\n- Real dependency graphs from real code\n\n## YOUR MISSION\nProve `salesforce-code-auditor` functionality with REAL Salesforce fixtures, not placeholders.\n\n## SPECIFIC REQUIREMENTS\n\n### 1. Create Real Test Fixtures\n- Create realistic Salesforce metadata samples:\n  - APEX classes (with typical patterns)\n  - LWC components (JavaScript + HTML)\n  - Visualforce pages\n  - Triggers\n  - Flows\n- Include both \"good\" and \"bad\" patterns for testing\n- Make fixtures representative of real Salesforce projects\n\n### 2. Test Full Audit Pipeline\n- Intake: Process fixture files\n- Analysis: Generate substantive findings\n- Reporting: Create usable audit reports\n- Integration: Verify outputs consumable by architect\n\n### 3. Verify Output Substance\n- Findings must be specific and technical\n- Not generic or placeholder findings\n- Include code locations, severity, recommendations\n- Reports must be complete and actionable\n\n### 4. Test Integration Readiness\n- Verify output format matches architect expectations\n- Test handoff from auditor to architect\n- Ensure project routing preserved\n- Verify artifacts stay in project folder\n\n## FILES TO CREATE\n1. `fixtures/real_salesforce_samples/` - Directory with real code samples\n2. `tests/test_with_real_fixtures.py` - Test script using real fixtures\n3. `evidence/audit_outputs/` - Generated audit reports as evidence\n4. `integration_test_report.md` - Report on architect ↔ auditor integration\n\n## DELIVERABLES\n1. **Real Salesforce fixtures** (not placeholders)\n2. **Audit evidence** showing:\n   - Real code processed (not simulated)\n   - Substantive findings generated\n   - Complete audit reports\n   - Technical specificity in findings\n3. **Integration evidence** showing outputs consumable by architect\n4. **Classification evidence** for certification:\n   - FUNCTIONAL if all tests pass with real data\n   - PARTIAL if some functions work but limitations exist\n   - SIMULATED if outputs are placeholder/descriptive only\n\n## EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS (Anti-simulation)\n- NO placeholder findings or empty reports\n- NO \"works with real code later\" claims\n- REAL code analysis with specific findings\n- REAL audit reports with actionable recommendations\n- REAL integration testing with architect\n\n## TEST SCENARIOS\n1. **APEX Analysis Test**: Process real APEX classes, find specific issues\n2. **LWC Analysis Test**: Process real Lightning Web Components\n3. **Dependency Graph Test**: Generate real dependency graphs\n4. **Integration Test**: Verify architect can consume audit outputs\n\n## TIMELINE\n- Start: Immediate\n- Complete: Within 30 minutes\n- Report: Concise handoff with evidence\n\n## SUCCESS CRITERIA\n`salesforce-code-auditor` classification depends on results:\n- **FUNCTIONAL**: All tests pass with real data, substantive findings\n- **PARTIAL**: Some functions work but limitations found\n- **SIMULATED**: Only placeholder outputs, no real analysis\n\nFocus on proving REAL functionality, not theoretical capability."}],"timestamp":1773101035504}}
{"type":"message","id":"63267327","parentId":"67ab2f3a","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:01.249Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I'll test the `salesforce-code-auditor` skill with real Salesforce fixtures. Let me start by examining the skill structure and then create realistic test fixtures."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_mAvBjQR85ohyVC6YaJloxzeH","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/salesforce-code-auditor/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-chat","usage":{"input":12235,"output":95,"cacheRead":2304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":14634,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773101035508}}
{"type":"message","id":"4247a09d","parentId":"63267327","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:01.267Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_mAvBjQR85ohyVC6YaJloxzeH","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: salesforce-code-auditor\ndescription: A production‑ready skill for progressive technical analysis of Salesforce codebases (Apex, LWC, Visualforce, Triggers, Flows, Metadata) with token‑efficient auditing.\nuser-invocable: true\ncommand-dispatch: salesforce-code-auditor\n---\n\n# Salesforce Code Auditor Skill\n\n## Overview\nA production‑ready skill for **progressive technical analysis of Salesforce codebases** (Apex, LWC, Visualforce, Triggers, Flows, Metadata) with **token‑efficient auditing**. The agent requests only the minimal necessary code to reconstruct the real execution logic of a process.\n\nDesigned to **work together with the `salesforce‑architect` skill** as a **subordinate validator** under architect governance.\n\n## HARDENED ARCHITECT INTEGRATION\n\n### Governance Relationship\nThe code‑auditor operates as a **subordinate validator** to the salesforce‑architect. All audits must be:\n- Project‑scoped under architect control\n- Invoked through defined handoff modes\n- Returning architect‑consumable outputs\n- Subject to architect review and validation\n\n### Handoff Modes (Governance Contract)\nThe architect invokes the auditor using defined handoff modes from `CODE_AUDIT_HANDOFF_MODES.md`:\n\n1. **Mode A — Architecture → Code Audit**\n   - **When**: Architect needs current‑state technical truth before design decisions\n   - **Request**: Clear audit objectives, scope, context\n   - **Response**: Technical assessment, constraints, recommendations\n\n2. **Mode B — Code Audit → Architecture**\n   - **When**: Audit findings must change architecture decisions\n   - **Request**: Focus on specific concerns, architectural context\n   - **Response**: Critical findings, architectural impact, remediation options\n\n3. **Mode C — Design Validation Mode**\n   - **When**: Architect needs to validate if implementation supports proposed design\n   - **Request**: Design context, validation objectives, specific points\n   - **Response**: Feasibility assessment, gap analysis, implementation complexity\n\n### Required Output Format for Architect Consumption\nAll audit reports must be structured for direct architect consumption:\n\n```\n## Code Audit Report - Mode <A/B/C>\n\n**Project**: <project_key>\n**Audit Case ID**: <case_id>\n**Mode**: <A/B/C>\n\n### Executive Summary\n- Overall code health assessment\n- Key findings summary\n- Architectural implications\n\n### Technical Assessment\n- Code structure and organization\n- Design patterns used\n- Technical debt identified\n- Performance characteristics\n\n### Constraints & Limitations\n- Technical constraints for new development\n- Integration limitations\n- Scalability constraints\n- Security limitations\n\n### Risk Assessment\n- **CRITICAL (Sev1)**: Security vulnerabilities, data loss risks, performance failures\n- **HIGH (Sev2)**: Significant security/performance issues, major code quality problems\n- **MEDIUM (Sev3)**: Code quality issues, performance optimizations, minor security concerns\n- **LOW (Sev4)**: Code style issues, documentation improvements, test coverage\n\n### Recommendations for Architecture\n1. <recommendation 1>\n2. <recommendation 2>\n3. <recommendation 3>\n\n### Evidence\n- Code snippets supporting findings\n- Performance metrics\n- Security vulnerability details\n- Design pattern analysis\n```\n\n### Blocking Conditions for Architectural Finalization\nFindings that **block architectural finalization**:\n- CRITICAL security vulnerabilities without approved mitigation\n- Architectural flaws requiring design changes\n- Performance issues making solution unusable\n- Integration failures preventing core functionality\n\n**Incident emission for blocking findings**: `salesforce|CODE_AUDIT|design_alignment_gap|review_required`\n\n## Workspace Code Intake Model\nThe user must place code inside a case folder created by the skill.\n\nDirectory created automatically:\n`<workspace>/projects/<project_key>/code_audit/<case_id>/inputs/`\n\nSupported formats:\n- Apex `.cls`\n- Apex Triggers `.trigger`\n- LWC `.js`, `.html`, `.xml`\n- Visualforce `.page`\n- Metadata `.xml`\n- Flow metadata\n- DTO / integration classes\n\nThe skill **indexes files first instead of reading them immediately**.\n\n## Required Runtime Structure\n```\n<workspace>/projects/<project_key>/code_audit/<case_id>/\n  CASE.md\n  inputs/\n  work/\n  snippets/\n  temp_analysis/\n  outputs/\n  INDEX.md\n  MANIFEST.json\n  DEPENDENCY_GRAPH.json\n  ENTRYPOINTS.json\n  EXECUTION_TRACE.md\n  FINDINGS.md\n  TEST_MATRIX.md\n  AUDIT_REPORT.md\n```\n\n## Skill Directory Structure\n```\nskills/salesforce-code-auditor/\n  SKILL.md (this file)\n  scripts/\n    init_case.py\n    index_inputs.py\n    detect_entrypoints.py\n    build_dependency_graph.py\n    extract_snippets.py\n    generate_reports.py\n    utils_fs.py\n  references/\n    FILE_TYPES.md\n    REVIEW_CHECKLISTS.md\n    TOKEN_STRATEGY.md\n    REPORT_TEMPLATE.md\n  examples/\n    example_intake.md\n    example_manifest.md\n    example_audit_report.md\n```\n\n## PROJECT STATE MACHINE INTEGRATION\n\n### Audit Timing in Project Lifecycle\nAudits must align with project state from `SALESFORCE_PROJECT_STATE_MACHINE.md`:\n\n1. **DISCOVERY phase**: Mode A audits to understand current codebase\n2. **DESIGN phase**: Mode C audits to validate design feasibility\n3. **ARCH_REVIEW phase**: Mode B audits for architectural validation\n4. **CODE_AUDIT phase**: Formal audit as part of state progression\n5. **REMEDIATION phase**: Follow‑up audits to validate fixes\n\n### State Transition Impact\n- **CODE_AUDIT → ARCH_REVIEW**: Findings may require architectural changes\n- **ARCH_REVIEW → REMEDIATION**: Critical findings require remediation\n- **REMEDIATION → FINALIZED**: All blocking findings must be resolved\n- **Any state → CODE_AUDIT**: Can trigger audit at any phase if needed\n\n### Project README Integration\nThe auditor must update project README with audit information:\n\n```\n## Code Audits\n- Case ID: <case_id>\n- Mode: <A/B/C>\n- Date: <timestamp>\n- Findings: <summary>\n- Status: <open / in remediation / closed>\n\n## Audit History\n- <case_id_1>: <date> - <mode> - <status>\n- <case_id_2>: <date> - <mode> - <status>\n```\n\n## Analysis Methodology\nReconstruct system behavior in this order:\n\n1 — UI Layer\n  Identify entry points: Visualforce pages, Lightning Web Components, Aura Components, Flow Screens\n  Detect: buttons, actions, Apex calls, events\n\n2 — Controller Layer\n  Analyze controller classes called by the UI.\n  Detect: invoked methods, validations, business logic, SOQL queries, DML operations\n\n3 — Auxiliary Classes\n  Trace additional classes used by controllers: service classes, utility classes, validators, parsers\n\n4 — Integration and DTO Layer\n  Identify classes responsible for: callouts, response parsing, external API integrations, DTO transport objects\n\n5 — Triggers\n  Detect triggers related to objects used by the process.\n  Analyze: trigger context events, automation side effects, recursive logic risks\n\n6 — Metadata and Automation\n  Detect: flows, process builders, platform events, async logic\n\n## Token Optimization Strategy\n**Never load all code simultaneously.**\n\nProcedure:\n1. Index files using `index_inputs.py`\n2. Detect entrypoints\n3. Request specific files or snippets\n4. Extract only required methods using `extract_snippets.py`\n\nThe analysis proceeds **incrementally**.\n\n## SFDX Support\nSupports both:\n- Option A — SFDX structure: `force-app/main/default/`\n- Option B — loose files in `inputs/`\n\nThe indexing script must detect both.\n\n## Dependency Reconstruction\n`build_dependency_graph.py` must generate `DEPENDENCY_GRAPH.json` containing:\n- class dependencies\n- method calls\n- trigger relationships\n- integration flows\n\n## Execution Trace\nGenerate `EXECUTION_TRACE.md` describing runtime order:\nUI → Controller → Services → Integrations → Triggers\n\n## Audit Findings\n`FINDINGS.md` must identify:\n- governor limit risks\n- SOQL in loops\n- missing FLS checks\n- mixed responsibilities\n- weak error handling\n- security vulnerabilities\n\n## Testing Matrix\nGenerate `TEST_MATRIX.md` containing:\n- scenario\n- trigger action\n- expected system behavior\n- related code location\n\n## Final Audit Report\n`AUDIT_REPORT.md` must include:\n- Summary\n- Architecture Observations\n- Technical Risks\n- Performance Risks\n- Security Risks\n- Refactor Opportunities\n- Design Alignment\n\nThe last section must compare the real code behaviour against outputs produced by the **salesforce‑architect skill** when available.\n\n## Integration with Learning System\nIf critical issues are detected append incidents to `workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md`.\n\nExample pattern keys:\n- `security|FLS_MISSING|apex`\n- `limits|SOQL_IN_LOOP|apex`\n- `architecture|MIXED_CONCERNS|controller`\n- `integration|UNHANDLED_CALLOUT_FAILURE`\n\nThen trigger error‑learning‑loop index rebuild fallback.\n\n## Demonstration Test\nRun a demo case: `demo_code_audit`\n\nThe test must:\n1. Create case folder\n2. Simulate input files\n3. Generate INDEX.md\n4. Build dependency graph\n5. Produce audit report\n\n## How to Use\n1. Ensure the skill directory is present.\n2. Run the pipeline:\n   ```bash\n   cd /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/skills/salesforce-code-auditor/scripts\n   python3 init_case.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   ```\n3. Place source files in the generated `inputs/` folder.\n4. Run the indexing:\n   ```bash\n   python3 index_inputs.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   ```\n5. Continue with detection, dependency graph, and reports.\n   ```bash\n   python3 detect_entrypoints.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   python3 build_dependency_graph.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   python3 generate_reports.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   ```\n6. For demo:\n   ```bash\n   python3 init_case.py --project-key demo --case-id demo_code_audit --demo\n   ```\n\n## Handoff Report Requirement\nEvery sub‑agent spawned by this skill must end its final response with a structured Handoff Report using this exact format:\n\n### Handoff Report\n- **Outcome**: success|partial|failure\n- **Incidents**:\n  - [TYPE=ERROR|NEAR_MISS|MISUNDERSTANDING|TOOL_FAILURE|MULTI_AGENT_HANDOFF; SEV=S1|S2|S3|S4] <brief symptom> (evidence: <1‑line concrete detail, no secrets>)\n  - Pattern hint: <optional>\n  - Prevention rule: <optional>\n- **Files touched**: <list or \"none\">\n- **Next action**: <1‑line suggestion>\n- **Watchdog fields** (required for monitoring):\n  - session_id: <your session identifier>\n  - run_id: <your run identifier>\n  - last_activity_at: <timestamp of last progress>\n  - progress_marker: <current step or checkpoint>\n\nIf no incidents occurred, write \"Incidents: none\"."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773101041260}}
